						               													<description>In Kitunda, a game for two to four players,  in which only the chess pawns are available for placement on an 8x8 field of play. The eight pawns of each player reside in a &amp;ldquo;trench or dugout&amp;rdquo; alongside the outer edges of the game board.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;A plague has crippled the &amp;ldquo;royals&amp;rdquo; (rooks, knights, bishops, and king) leaving the queens of four different nations to attend to them. The Kitunda, Swahili for chess pawns, are given a crystal (die), which they can use to access the powers of the royals.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Each roll of a die allows any pawn to enter the field of play using the capability of a royal piece. For example, a 1 on a die allows any chess pawn to move like a rook. While a 6 allows any pawn to move like a bishop, and so on.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The objective is to capture all opposing pawns until only one victorious player remains.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;-description from designer&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
